                     <lb n="9"/><w part="I">Εὐκ</w><gap reason="illegible" quantity="2" unit="character"/><gap reason="lost" extent="unknown" unit="character"/>
                </ab>
            </div>
            <div type="apparatus">
                <listApp>
                    <app><note>Text after Merlini 1841</note></app>
                    <app loc="4"><rdg>Merlini reports a small circle upper right of the N, and traces of what might be a capital T after the second b</rdg></app>
                    <app loc="7"><rdg>Merlini reports a small circle upper right of the first N</rdg></app>
                    <app loc="8"><rdg>ΚΡΑΤΓΣΤΟΣ <note>Merlini 1841</note></rdg> <rdg>Κράτυλος <note>Messina 1992</note></rdg></app>
                </listApp>
            </div>
            <div type="translation">
                <p><!--translation(s) - add @xml:lang for 'en' or 'it' to div--></p>
            </div>
            <div type="commentary">
                <p>Orsi's transcription and editing of the original report of Merlini is not entirely faithful, and Messina's reading of lines 8-9 as another name seems preferable. The symbols left uninterpreted by Orsi must be numerals and find approximate parallels (even if not certain interpretation) among other later Hellenistic Sicilian texts (see e.g. the gallery texts from the Euryalos fortifications).
                    <!--a text reported in antiquarian tradition as 'epi hieropolou ...tos Apolloniou .... Nbb Theodoros Pollodorou ... NNb Kratystos euk...; Orsi trieds to improve the reading, noting implication of a sanctuary and college of priests.--></p>
            </div>
